<p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The following are some frequently asked questions about installing and using Service Management Automation X (SMAX).</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Installation">Installation</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="How_do_I_know_the_image_tag_for_pods?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="How_do_I_know_the_image_tag_for_pods.3F">How do I know the image tag for pods?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Run the following command:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><code style="font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; color: rgb(51, 51, 51) !important; padding: 2px 5px !important; font-size: 16px;">kubectl describe pods &lt;pod names&gt; -n &lt;namespace&gt;</code></p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_should_I_do_if_one_of_my_pods_fails?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_should_I_do_if_one_of_my_pods_fails.3F">What should I do if one of my pods fails?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Run the following command:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><code style="font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; color: rgb(51, 51, 51) !important; padding: 2px 5px !important; font-size: 16px;">kubectl delete pod &lt;name of the pod that failed&gt; -n &lt;namespace&gt;</code></p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Is_there_a_way_to_remove_and_restart_the_suite_image_installation?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Is_there_a_way_to_remove_and_restart_the_suite_image_installation.3F">Is there a way to remove and restart the suite&nbsp;image installation?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">My Service Management Automation&nbsp;suite installation failed somewhere. I had issues with the image push and one image was not pushed.&nbsp;</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Re-import the images by running the image import script again. You can run the image import script multiple times. For more information, see&nbsp;<a href="https://docs.microfocus.com/itom/SMAX:2019.08/downloadContainerImages" title="SMAX:2019.08/downloadContainerImages" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); text-decoration-line: none; font-size: 15px !important;">Download the container images</a>.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Where_are_the_docker_proxy_settings_stored_in_the_CDF_environment?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Where_are_the_docker_proxy_settings_stored_in_the_CDF_environment.3F">Where are the docker proxy settings stored in the CDF environment?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">These settings are in both the /usr/lib/systemd/system/docker.service.d and /usr/lib/systemd/system/docker-bootstrap.service.d in the&nbsp;<b>http_proxy.conf</b>&nbsp;files.</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">[Service]</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Environment= "http_proxy=<span class="nolink">http://&lt;proxy&gt;:&lt;port&gt;</span>" "https_proxy=<span class="nolink">http://&lt;proxy&gt;:&lt;port&gt;</span>" "no_proxy=localhost,127.0.0.1"</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">If the proxy is configured incorrectly, you cannot run&nbsp;<b>downloadimages.sh</b>&nbsp;successfully. After updating these proxy settings, run&nbsp;<b>kube-restart.sh</b>&nbsp;from /opt/kubernetes/bin, and then&nbsp;<b>downloadimages.sh</b>&nbsp;should work.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="How_do_I_know_the_namespace_being_used_for_Service_Management_Automation?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="How_do_I_know_the_namespace_being_used_for_Service_Management_Automation.3F">How do I know the namespace being used for Service Management Automation?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">ITOM Platform supports only one instance of the suite. It automatically assigns a namespace (itsma-xxxxx) for your suite&nbsp;installation. To see the namespace being used for your current suite&nbsp;installation, log in to CDF, and then navigate to&nbsp;<b>SUITE</b>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<b>Management</b>.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_should_I_do_if_an_suite_update_fails?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_should_I_do_if_an_suite_update_fails.3F">What should I do if an suite update fails?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">When I upgrade the suite images from the CDF user interface (<b>SUITE</b>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<b>Management</b>&nbsp;&gt; More Actions icon (<span class="confluence-embedded-file-wrapper"><a class="image" title="19895688.png" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); font-size: 15px !important;"><img alt="19895688.png" src="https://docs.microfocus.com/mediawiki/images/9/90/2018.02/attachments/19895687/19895688.png" width="15" height="25" class="confluence-embedded-image" data-file-width="15" data-file-height="25" style="border: none; max-width: 100%; height: auto; width: auto; margin: auto 0px;"></a></span>) &gt;&nbsp;<b>Update</b>), after I click&nbsp;<b>NEXT</b>&nbsp;on the storage configuration page, a message "The https://&lt;ingresshost&gt;/update might be temporarily down or it may have moved permanently to a new web address." is displayed.</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Follow the steps below to reload this page and finish the suite update.</p><ol style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-top: 0px; margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; font-size: 18px;"><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Log in to the&nbsp;<span class="nolink"><b>https://&lt;ingresshost&gt;/update</b></span>&nbsp;page on a new tab in the same browser.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Reload the frame on the suite upgrade page where an error message is displayed.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Click&nbsp;<b>APPLY</b>&nbsp;on the page that opens to finish the suite update.</li></ol><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_should_I_do_if_I_cannot_uninstall_the_suite_from_the_CDF_user_interface?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_should_I_do_if_I_cannot_uninstall_the_suite_from_the_CDF_user_interface.3F">What should I do if I cannot uninstall the suite from the CDF user interface?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">I want to uninstall Service Management Automation&nbsp;because the installation failed. However, the Uninstall menu option (<b>SUITE</b>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<b>Management</b>&nbsp;&gt; More Action icon&nbsp;<span class="confluence-embedded-file-wrapper"><a class="image" title="19895688.png" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); font-size: 15px !important;"><img alt="19895688.png" src="https://docs.microfocus.com/mediawiki/images/9/90/2018.02/attachments/19895687/19895688.png" width="15" height="25" class="confluence-embedded-image" data-file-width="15" data-file-height="25" style="border: none; max-width: 100%; height: auto; width: auto; margin: auto 0px;"></a></span>&gt;&nbsp;<b>Uninstall</b>) does not work. What should I do?</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Recreate the suite-db pods with the following commands:</p><pre style="font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.25em; margin-top: 4px; margin-bottom: 4px; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240); padding: 1em; white-space: pre-wrap; word-break: normal;">kubectl get pods -n core

kubectl delete pod &lt;pod name of suite-db&gt; -n core</pre><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Alternatively, you can restart the virtual machine where the suite-db is installed.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Load_balancing">Load balancing</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_if_the_customer_plans_to_use_a_Citrix-based_load_balancer_outside_of_Service_Management_Automation?_Will_there_be_any_impact_on_the_suite_load_balancer?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_if_the_customer_plans_to_use_a_Citrix-based_load_balancer_outside_of_Service_Management_Automation.3F_Will_there_be_any_impact_on_the_suite_load_balancer.3F">What if the customer plans to use a Citrix-based load balancer outside of Service Management Automation? Will there be any impact on the suite load balancer?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">As the Service Management Automation suite has its own load balancer already, it does not need an external load balancer.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Do_we_really_need_an_external_load_balancer_if_the_suite_is_providing_a_load_balancer_itself?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Do_we_really_need_an_external_load_balancer_if_the_suite_is_providing_a_load_balancer_itself.3F">Do we really need an external load balancer if the suite is providing a load balancer itself?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">As the suite has its own load balancer already, it does not need an external load balancer.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="If_an_external_load_balancer_is_also_used,_will_the_external_load_balancer_connect_with_the_suite_load_balancer?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="If_an_external_load_balancer_is_also_used.2C_will_the_external_load_balancer_connect_with_the_suite_load_balancer.3F">If an external load balancer is also used, will the external load balancer connect with the suite load balancer?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">As suite has its own load balancer already, it does not need an external Load Balancer. In the event that you have already had an external load balancer, it connects to the suite&nbsp;load balancer.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Database_support">Database support</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="How_do_I_access_the_internal_Postgres_database_for_the_suite_CMDB?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="How_do_I_access_the_internal_Postgres_database_for_the_suite_CMDB.3F">How do I access the internal Postgres database for the suite&nbsp;CMDB?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">If CMDB uses the internal Postgres database, can I open the Postgres UI and browse through the contents of the database?</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:&nbsp;</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The&nbsp;CMDB's Postgres database in the suite has an exposed node port. You can use an external Postgres client to access the database server and browse through the contents of the database.&nbsp;</p><div class="table-wrap" style="font-size: 18px;"><a class="buttonfullscr" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); font-size: 15px !important;"><button class="flscrbtn" style="max-height: 40px; font-size: 15px !important;"><span class="material-icons flscricn">open_in_new</span><div style="margin: auto 5px;">View Fullscreen</div></button></a><table style="width: 255px; margin-top: 5px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium;"><tbody><tr><td>CMDB Postgres port</td><td>31402</td></tr><tr><td>CMDB Browser ports</td><td>31403, 31404</td></tr><tr><td>CMDB Server ports</td><td>31400, 31401</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_are_the_requirements_for_using_Oracle_databases_for_the_containerized_CMDB?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_are_the_requirements_for_using_Oracle_databases_for_the_containerized_CMDB.3F">What are the requirements for using Oracle databases for the containerized CMDB?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The configuration is the same as the classic configuration.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Is_one_PostgreSQL_database_enough_for_production?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Is_one_PostgreSQL_database_enough_for_production.3F">Is one PostgreSQL database enough for production?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">It is recommended to use HA enabled external PostgreSQL database for production. There are several PG HA solutions in the community and commercial support is also available in the market.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_is_stored_into_database_and_file_system?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_is_stored_into_database_and_file_system.3F">What is stored into database and file system?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The database stores all transactional and foundational data, such as tickets, changes, CIs, People, Locations, and general Codeless Configuration data. The file system stores attachments and search index data.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Is_it_recommended_to_have_a_cluster_about_database_and_file_system?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Is_it_recommended_to_have_a_cluster_about_database_and_file_system.3F">Is it recommended to have a cluster about database and file system?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Yes, a clustered/redundant DB server and NFS server are also recommended for production use.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_I_have_any_desynchronization_between_file_system_and_database?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_I_have_any_desynchronization_between_file_system_and_database.3F">Can I have any desynchronization between file system and database?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:<br>Can I have any desynchronization between file system and database? It could be a problem if the application is up and the database is down. What happens to the file system?<br></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Transactional and application data is stored in the database. The file system stores logs, IDOL index files, and some deployment configuration and property files. In the case of the database being down, the full system will be out of service too. All application transactions rely on DB operations, and this includes user login and authentication. So, although the file system may work fine, desynchronization is not an issue as the application would not be interacting with it until the database service is back. Also, compared to DB access, files on the file system are changed far less frequently.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Master_data_onboarding">Master data onboarding</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="How_do_I_push_CIs_from_a_standalone_UCMDB_to_the_suite_CMDB?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="How_do_I_push_CIs_from_a_standalone_UCMDB_to_the_suite_CMDB.3F">How do I push CIs from a standalone UCMDB to the suite CMDB?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Question details</b>:<br></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">I have the suite installed and have the standalone UCMDB. I want to push the CIs from the standalone UCMDB to the suite CMDB. What are the URL and host details that I should give the standalone UCMDB?</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The current release supports pushing CIs from a standalone UCMDB to the suite&nbsp;CMDB. Refer to&nbsp;<a href="https://docs.microfocus.com/itom/Universal_CMDB:2019.05/IntegPushJob" title="Universal CMDB:2019.05/IntegPushJob" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); text-decoration-line: none; font-size: 15px !important;">How to Work with Data Push Jobs</a>&nbsp;for the&nbsp;URL and host details.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span id="Identity_Manager_(IDM)"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Identity_Manager_.28IDM.29">Identity Manager (IDM)</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_is_the_role_of_IDM_in_the_suite?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_is_the_role_of_IDM_in_the_suite.3F">What is the role of IDM in the suite?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>IDM is used for user authentication. IDM connects to the customer's LDAP server.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="DNS">DNS</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_is_the_role_of_DNS_in_the_suite?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_is_the_role_of_DNS_in_the_suite.3F">What is the role of DNS in the suite?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Kubernetes DNS in the suite&nbsp;is only used for internal services.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_we_configure_or_use_external_DNS?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_we_configure_or_use_external_DNS.3F">Can we configure or use external DNS?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>No.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Integrations">Integrations</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_happens_if_the_suite_load_balancer_fails_or_crashes?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_happens_if_the_suite_load_balancer_fails_or_crashes.3F">What happens if the suite&nbsp;load balancer fails or crashes?&nbsp;</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b><i>:</i></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">The suite provides a self-recovery mechanism for the load balancer.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_we_configure_external_mail_servers_for_notifications_in_the_suite?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_we_configure_external_mail_servers_for_notifications_in_the_suite.3F">Can we configure external mail servers for notifications in the suite?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b><i>:</i></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Yes, the suite can work with an external mail server, which can be configured from the&nbsp;<b>Suite Administration</b>interface.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Reverse_proxy">Reverse proxy</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_is_the_role_of_Reverse_Proxy?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_is_the_role_of_Reverse_Proxy.3F">What is the role of Reverse Proxy?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer:</b></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">It is Nginx-based, the single gateway for incoming traffic. It works for routing, and authentication gateway.</p><h2 style="margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Miscellaneous">Miscellaneous</span></h2><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_should_I_do_if_a_502_error_occurs_when_users_attempt_to_log_in_to_the_suite?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_should_I_do_if_a_502_error_occurs_when_users_attempt_to_log_in_to_the_suite.3F">What should I do if a 502 error occurs when users attempt to log in to the suite?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br></p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Perform the following steps on a master node to restart the frontend ingress:</p><ol style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-top: 0px; margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; font-size: 18px;"><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Run the command below to get the pod name:<pre style="font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; line-height: 1.25em; margin-top: 4px; margin-bottom: 4px; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240); padding: 1em; white-space: pre-wrap; word-break: normal;">kubectl get pod  -n &lt;suite namespace&gt; |grep nginx</pre></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Run the command below to delete the pod:<pre style="font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; line-height: 1.25em; margin-top: 4px; margin-bottom: 4px; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240); padding: 1em; white-space: pre-wrap; word-break: normal;">kubectl delete pod &lt;pod name&gt; -n &lt;suite namespace&gt;</pre></li></ol><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_I_have_part_of_the_application_in_K8S_and_part_of_the_application_(for_example,_database_and_file_system)_in_legacy_mode?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_I_have_part_of_the_application_in_K8S_and_part_of_the_application_.28for_example.2C_database_and_file_system.29_in_legacy_mode.3F">Can I have part of the application in K8S and part of the application (for example, database and file system) in legacy mode?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Yes. Database and file system can be in legacy mode, meaning that they are external and not managed by K8S.&nbsp;<br></p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Which_component_uses_RabbitMQ_?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Which_component_uses_RabbitMQ_.3F">Which component uses RabbitMQ&nbsp;?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>The Service Portal is using RabbitMQ.<br></p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Which_part_is_critical_for_a_reboot?_If_I_reboot_the_database_(not_in_K8S),_is_the_application_able_to_go_on_without_rebooting_itself?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Which_part_is_critical_for_a_reboot.3F_If_I_reboot_the_database_.28not_in_K8S.29.2C_is_the_application_able_to_go_on_without_rebooting_itself.3F">Which part is critical for a reboot? If I reboot the database (not in K8S), is the application able to go on without rebooting itself?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>If multi-master is deployed, the sequence of rebooting master nodes is critical because K8S needs at least two master nodes functioning to keep the cluster running.<br>If database is rebooted, some of the pods will get restarted by K8S because the liveness check failed due to database error. Once the database is back again, the pods will come back as well.<br></p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Which_solution_do_you_advice_to_monitor_ITSMA?_Prometheus_with_Grafana_and_AlertManager?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Which_solution_do_you_advice_to_monitor_ITSMA.3F_Prometheus_with_Grafana_and_AlertManager.3F">Which solution do you advice to monitor ITSMA? Prometheus with Grafana and AlertManager?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>We recommend Prometheus with Grafana.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Is_it_easy_to_export_docker_images_between_two_machines?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Is_it_easy_to_export_docker_images_between_two_machines.3F">Is it easy to export docker images between two machines?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Yes. It is quite easy to do this using the ‘docker save/load’ or ‘docker export/import’ command.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_I_verify_the_logs_from_outside_of_Linux_server?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_I_verify_the_logs_from_outside_of_Linux_server.3F">Can I verify the logs from outside of Linux server?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>Yes, the log files are the same. But the logs viewed in management portal are just stdout. There are more files on log volume.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_operations_cannot_be_performed_from_the_management_portal_UI,_and_I_have_to_log_in_to_the_K8S_server?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_operations_cannot_be_performed_from_the_management_portal_UI.2C_and_I_have_to_log_in_to_the_K8S_server.3F">What operations cannot be performed from the management portal UI, and I have to log in to the K8S server?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer:</b><br>The management portal manages the K8S resources only. So in the cases like below, you will need to log in to the servers:<br></p><ul style="margin-left: 18px; margin-top: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 18px;"><li>You encounter issues around Docker or Kubernetes cluster status, for example, a node is not reachable, or Docker crashes.<br></li><li>You need advanced functions that are only available with command line:<br><ul style="margin-left: 18px; margin-top: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em;">Using CDF command lines, for example, kube-stop and kube-restart.<br></li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em;">Going into the Docker container for trouble shooting, for example, kubectl exec –it.<br>See&nbsp;<a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/overview/" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); text-decoration-line: none; font-size: 15px !important;">https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/overview/</a>&nbsp;for more details.<br></li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em;">Using Docker commands, for example, docker inspect and docker pull.<br></li></ul></li><li>You want to view more detailed logs.&nbsp;<br>The detailed logs are not visible in the management portal. However, it’s not required to log in to the K8S server specifically. Any Linux box that can access the NFS volume should work fine.</li></ul><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_are_the_recommended_possibilities_to_monitor_the_suite?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_are_the_recommended_possibilities_to_monitor_the_suite.3F">What are the recommended possibilities to monitor the suite?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">From the CDF portal, click&nbsp;<b>LAUNCH DASHBOARD</b>, under&nbsp;<b>Namespace</b>&nbsp;choose the suite namespace to make sure all deployments and pods are in desired status.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="What_are_the_items_that_we_have_to_monitor_to_ensure_that_the_suite_works_correctly?_Can_we_use_a_product_like_Zabbix_or_BMC_TrueSight_for_monitoring?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="What_are_the_items_that_we_have_to_monitor_to_ensure_that_the_suite_works_correctly.3F_Can_we_use_a_product_like_Zabbix_or_BMC_TrueSight_for_monitoring.3F">What are the items that we have to monitor to ensure that the suite works correctly? Can we use a product like Zabbix or BMC TrueSight for monitoring?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">Currently, we leverage Kubernetes/Docker level monitoring, and we have a whitepaper on Prometheus. For more details, see&nbsp;<a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://blog.kubernetes.io/2017/05/kubernetes-monitoring-guide.html" style="color: rgb(58, 131, 230); text-decoration-line: none; font-size: 15px !important;">http://blog.kubernetes.io/2017/05/kubernetes-monitoring-guide.html</a>.</p><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;">There are several levels of monitoring:</p><ul style="margin-left: 18px; margin-top: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 18px;"><li>Infra: NFS volume, VM hosts, and infra networking</li><li>Kubernetes nodes&nbsp;: CPU, Memory, Network IO, available disk spaces for all disk partitions</li><li>Docker containers: CPU, Memory, Network IO</li><li>Suite application: Customer can set up the monitoring the same way as the classic deployment by accessing the applications through URL.</li></ul><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="How_Can_I_modify_the_information_displayed_in_forms_of_SMA_Service_Portal?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="How_Can_I_modify_the_information_displayed_in_forms_of_SMA_Service_Portal.3F">How Can I modify the information displayed in forms of SMA Service Portal?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>You can use&nbsp;<b>Administration &gt; Studio</b>&nbsp;to change or design forms.</p><h3 style="margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px; border-bottom: none; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; font-size: 18px !important;"><span id="Can_I_modify_the_search_fields_in_Service_Portal?"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Can_I_modify_the_search_fields_in_Service_Portal.3F">Can I modify the search fields in Service Portal?</span></h3><p style="margin: 0px 0px 12px; font-size: 18px;"><b>Answer</b>:<br>No, they cannot be customized for now.</p>